Ali, looking at the TPTP definition of "major": http://www.eclipse.org/tptp/home/documents/process/development/bugzilla.html, are you saying that once this error appears that the log interaction view cannot be used at all for any logs? If not then please downgrade this to "normal".
I see the priority was changed from P1 to P2. Isn't the priority set by the requestor? I believe this is a P1 from consumer's point of view.

The priority is set by the assignee and the severity is set by the requestor. The full explanation can be found in the official docs http://www.eclipse.org/tptp/home/documents/process/development/bugzilla.html. In TPTP the priority field is a promise when the fix will go into the release named in the Target Milestone field. 

Here's a quicker summary for you. Roughly:
   P1 means that TPTP promises that the fix will be checked in the named release
   P2 means that TPTP agrees that the fix is important and will try, but cannot guarantee, that the fix will be in the named release
   P3 ... well it usually means that someone hasn't got around to setting the priority, but if it's really a P3 it means "TPTP will look into this if there's a chance, but don't expect it in the named release"

The priority was changed from P1 to P2 because I haven't had a chance to find out what's causing the problem and thus I can't promise anything. P2 means that it will be investigated in TPTP V4.3 and if I can figure out what's wrong and if I can find a safe fix then the fix will be checked into TPTP V4.3.
Defer these defects to 4.4 because they can't be contained by end of day today and they're not on any critical list.
